{"metadata":{"symbolKind":"module","role":"collection","externalID":"Tuplé","roleHeading":"Framework","modules":[{"name":"Tuplé"}],"title":"Tuplé"},"hierarchy":{"paths":[[]]},"topicSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tuple-\/Type-Aliases","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tuple-\/Properties","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tuple-\/Instance-Methods","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tuple-\/Type","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tupl-\/Swift\/Sequence"],"anchor":"Topics"}],"abstract":[{"text":"Bridge the gap between tuples and ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/collections","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"major":0,"minor":3},"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/tupl-"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"kind":"symbol","sections":[],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"text":"Overview","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"overview"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Despite tuples being very much like fixed-count arrays, they are not equipped with much of the built-in functionality that is provided for any type of collection in the standard library. ☹️","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This package addresses some of the omissions, bringing tuples and collections closer to feature parity."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"text":"“Geneity”","level":4,"anchor":"Geneity","type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Swift’s collections are homogeneous, meaning they’re generic over their ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/collection\/element","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":". Some of what’s in this package does require the tuples you’re working with to be homogeneous, as well."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"But it’s generally no more complex to support working with heterogeneous tuples, so this package defers to the choice of maximum versatility, supporting homogeneous tuples as a subset of heterogenous ones."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For example, the code for reversing an "},{"code":"(Int, String)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":":"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["reversed((1, \"Two\"))"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"…also supports "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"(Int, Int)"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"code":["reversed((1, 2))"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Element Count","anchor":"Element-Count","level":4},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"This package will support arbitrary-count tuples, incorporating the evolution of ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-evolution\/blob\/main\/proposals\/0393-parameter-packs.md"},{"type":"text","text":", when possible."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Otherwise, the cap for support is tuples with "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"4 elements"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":". This is the de facto size limit found in 3D graphics frameworks such as ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/realitykit","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" and libraries such as "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/simd-vector-types","isActive":true},{"text":" and  ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/spatial","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":". Supporting visionOS development by filling in tuple-shaped holes in that Apple-provided software is a primary motivator for this package, but it is otherwise unrelated to graphics."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"level":5,"anchor":"Usage-Examples","type":"heading","text":"Usage Examples"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"You’ve got the source code, so aside from reading this documentation, see the ","type":"text"},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Tests"}]},{"type":"text","text":" folder for example usage! 😺"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tupl-","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"references":{"https://developer.apple.com/documentation/swift/simd-vector-types":{"title":"SIMD","url":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/simd-vector-types","type":"link","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/simd-vector-types","titleInlineContent":[{"text":"SIMD","type":"text"}]},"doc://xn--tupl-epa/documentation/Tuple-/Properties":{"type":"topic","kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/tuple-\/properties","title":"Properties","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Functions that would be properties if tuples could be extended."}],"role":"collectionGroup","identifier":"doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tuple-\/Properties"},"https://developer.apple.com/documentation/swift/collections":{"title":"Collections","url":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/collections","type":"link","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/collections","titleInlineContent":[{"text":"Collections","type":"text"}]},"doc://xn--tupl-epa/documentation/Tuple-/Type-Aliases":{"url":"\/documentation\/tuple-\/type-aliases","title":"Type Aliases","identifier":"doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tuple-\/Type-Aliases","role":"collectionGroup","kind":"article","type":"topic","abstract":[{"text":"Shorthand syntax for tuples.","type":"text"}]},"doc://xn--tupl-epa/documentation/Tupl-/Swift/Sequence":{"kind":"symbol","fragments":[{"text":"extension","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"Sequence","preciseIdentifier":"s:ST","kind":"identifier"}],"title":"Sequence","type":"topic","url":"\/documentatio